occurrences.line_text: What and from whence she was, and by what traine
Kept, and deliuered me from deadly dread.
Far from all neighbourhood, the which annoy it may.
From his deuotion streight he troubled was;
From all this worlds incombraunce did himselfe assoyle.
From your owne will, to cure your maladie.
From things, that stirre vp fraile affection;
From that they most affect, and in due termes containe.
For from those outward sences ill affected,
At sight thereof, and from her presence flee:
In fearefull darkenesse, furthest from the skie,
And from the earth, appointed haue her place,
Abstaine from pleasure, and restraine your will,
Would he restrayned be from his attendement.
He fled from roome to roome, from place to place,
He fled from roome to roome, from place to place,
And with her garment couering him from sight,
Gan him recomfort, and from ground to reare.
So hauing from his crauen bodie torne
Whom when the Saluage saw from daunger free,
Ne secretly from thought of fell reuenge surceasse.
Tooke surer hould, and from his horses backe
So different from that, which earst ye seem'd in sight?
He would haue backe retyred from that sight,
Had for his food late gathered from the tree,
Or kept in bands, or from their loues exyled,
Were bound about, and voyded from before,
That forst him th'halter from his hand to loose,
Quites Mirabell from dreed:
He from you take that chiefedome, which ye doe abuse.
But cruelty and hardnesse from you chace,
And from you turne the loue of men to hate.
Who from the high degree of happy state,
Abide, and from them lay your loathly hands;
No more then lightening from the lofty sky.
From whence ere he recouery could gaine,
Vppon that Carle, to saue his friend from ieopardy.
His head meant from his shoulders to haue swept.
From that vnwares ye weetlesse doe intend;
Deliuer from the doome of my desart,
Who was so far from being ought amazed,
He from those bands weend him to haue vnwound.
And from him taking his owne whip, therewith
Whether I shall you leaue, or from these villaines lose.
A great aduenture, which did him from them deuide.
She from her palfrey lighted on the plaine,
So being stayd, they her from thence directed
And groning sore from grieued hart entire,
From them returning to that Ladie backe,
That so rich frute should be from vs bereft;
Him first from court he to the citties coursed,
And from the citties to the townes him prest,
And from the townes into the countrie forsed,
And from the country back to priuate farmes he scorsed.
From thence into the open fields he fled,
They prayd high God him farre from them to send.
From all the tempests of these worldly seas,
Sometime the fawne I practise from the Doe,
Or from the Goat her kidde how to conuay;
My limbes in euery shade, to rest from toyle,
From natiue home, and spent my youth in vaine,
I from thenceforth haue learn'd to loue more deare
From pitch of higher place, vnto this low degree.
That whether quite from them for to retrate
From malicing, or grudging his good houre,
Or litle sparrowes, stolen from their nest,
Her flowry garlond tooke from her owne head,
From chacing him, till he had it attchieued?
With grace from her, whose loue his heart hath sore engrieued.
That from henceforth he meanes no more to sew
From so high step to stoupe vnto so low.
He chaunst to come, far from all peoples troad,
Keeping all noysome things away from it,
But why when I them saw, fled they away from me?
As he this way comming from feastfull glee,
Simple and true from couert malice free:
That good should from vs goe, then come in greater store.
With heauenly gifts from heuen first enraced?
Thus to bereaue thy Loues deare sight from thee:
Like as the wounded Whale to shore flies fro[m] the maine.
Who scarcely yet from former feare exempted,
From that day forth she gan him to affect,
Both his estate, and loue from skill of any wight.
Mote them descry, nor reskue from their pray,
From view of liuing wight, and couered ouer:
Her Calidore from them redeemes,
And pitty her sad plight, so chang'd from pleasaunt hew.
From that day forth he kyndnesse to her showed,
So from thenceforth, when loue he to her made,
To stay their cruell hands from slaughter fell.
Of those, that hauing saued her from dying,
Who when he backe returned from the wood,
As if he did from some late daunger fly,
Or other dyrefull hap from heauen or hell
Spoyld all our cots, and caried vs from hence?
From Meliboe and from themselues whyleare,
From Meliboe and from themselues whyleare,
What mister men, and eke from whence they were.
Had from their maisters fled, & now sought hyre elswhere.
Fled from his wrath, and did themselues conuay
Into their caues, their heads from death to hide,
Deuiz'd all goodly meanes, from her to driue
Which they from many long had robd and rent,
Had reft from Meliboe, and from his make,
Had reft from Meliboe, and from his make,
This gentle knight, from sewing his first quest,
Faire Pastorella from those Brigants powre,
And ransacke all their dennes from most to least,
From thence into the sacred Church he broke,
From blamefull blot, and free from all that wite,
From blamefull blot, and free from all that wite,
That bloud-red billowes like a walled front
His snowy front curled with golden heares,
Did front him face to face against him bent,
Their horned fronts so fierce on either side
An aged sire with head all frory hore,
And with his frory lips full softly kist,
Shortly they reard out of her frosen swownd;
To doe the frosen cold away to fly;
All night in old Tithonus frosen bed,
Yet in his frosen members did remaine,
Ne in their frosen hearts feele kindly flame:
As hoarie frost with spangles doth attire
Ne suffred storme nor frost on them to fall,
And sprinckled frost vpon his deawy beard:
Of th'Oceans fruitfull froth, did first appeare:
Of his froth-fomy steed, whose courage stout
The yron rowels into frothy fome he bit.
Ye might haue seene the frothy billowes fry
Some frounce their curled haire in courtly guise,
On you hath fround, and pourd his influence bad,
This fround, that faund, the third for shame did blush,
Thereof did in his frouning face appeare:
But thou, sweet Babe, whom frowning froward fate
All for their Ladies froward loue to gaine,
And those two froward sisters, their faire loues
She scould, and frownd with froward countenaunce,
But that same froward twaine would accourage,
Of froward fortune shall be forst to yield.
But froward fortune, and too forward Night
When so the froward skye began to lowre:
With froward will doth set him selfe to weepe;
Whom when those knights so froward and forlore
That two of them still fr[ow]ard seem'd to bee,
Who in his frowardnesse from her was fled;
She scould, and frownd with froward countenaunce,
Which when the other heard, she sternly frownd
Thereat frown'd Coridon, and his lip closely bit.
The storme of fortunes frowne, or heauens threat,
And at her happinesse do fret and frowne:
Vpon their blisse, and balefull fortune frowne.
Fortune enuying good, hath felly frowned,
Their frowning forheads with rough hornes yclad,
But thou, sweet Babe, whom frowning froward fate
Haue not all seized on your frozen hart,
To gin awake, and stirre his frozen spright:
For her faint heart was with the frozen cold
That in her pregnant flesh they shortly fructifide.
To bring forth fruit, and make eternall derth,
If Bacchus merry fruit they did inuent,
Till that with timely fruit her belly sweld,
Whereon nor fruit, nor leafe was euer seene,
Loaden with fruit and apples rosie red,
Her daintie paps; which like young fruit in May
Deserues to tast his follies fruit, repented payne.
And loaden all with fruit as thicke as it might bee.
Their fruit were golden apples glistring bright,
And planted there, did bring forth fruit of gold:
Here also sprong that goodly golden fruit,
To reach the fruit, which grew vpon the brincke:
But both the fruit from hand, and floud from mouth
Why takest not of that same fruit of gold,
But thou thy treasons fruit, I hope, shalt taste
And with her right the riper fruit did reach,
That but the fruit more sweetnesse did containe,
Both leafe and fruit, both too vntimely shed,
And beareth fruit of honour and all chast desire.
Now Bacchus fruit out of the siluer plate
Each other of loues bitter fruit despoile.
Such is the powre of that same fruit, that nought
The fruite of ioy and blisse, though long time dearely bought.
The fruitfull Oliue, and the Platane round,
And partly female of his fruitfull seed;
Her fruitfull cursed spawne of serpents small,
Was woxen strong, and left her fruitfull nest;
Adornd with fruitfull Oliues all arownd,
And freely sprong out of the fruitfull ground,
Of many Dragonets, his fruitfull seed;
By great Dame Nature, from whose fruitfull pap
Out of her fruitfull lap; how, no man knowes,
Not such, as earth out of her fruitfull woomb
Both faire and fruitfull, and the ground dispred
Of th'Oceans fruitfull froth, did first appeare:
Whiles fruitfull Ceres, and Lyï¿½us fat
Thy fruitfull Ofspring, shall from thee descend;
The fruitfull plaines, and with fell cruelty,
Be freshly kindled in the fruitfull Ile
Through influence of th'heauens fruitfull ray,
But reason teacheth that the fruitfull seades
It sited was in fruitfull soyle of old,
And all the fruitfull spawne of fishes hew
The substances of natures fruitfull progenyes.
And from their fruitfull sides sweet gum did drop,
And largely ouerflow the fruitfull plaine,
Or of the fruitfull liquor ouerflowne,
Fruitfull of all things fit for liuing foode,
He turnd himselfe into a fruitfull vine,
And fruitfull apples to haue borne awhile,
Out of her fruitfull lap aboundant flowres,
To all the Sea-gods and their fruitfull seede,
The pleasant Boyne, the fishy fruitfull Ban,
Whose fruitfull seede farre passeth those in land,
And with strong hand their fruitfull rancknes did deface.
The fruitfull vine, whose liquor blouddy red
Or fruitfullest Virginia who did euer vew?
And eke the fruitfull-headed beast, amaz'd
The ioyes whereof, and happie fruitfulnesse,
Arriu'd, where they in erth their fruitles bloud had sown.
Like fruitles seede, of which vntimely death should grow.
That him to follow was but fruitlesse paine;
Backe to the world, whose ioyes so fruitlesse are;
Bid thee to them thy fruitlesse labours yield,
Refuse such fruitlesse toile, and present pleasures chuse.
Whom he had long time sought with fruitlesse suit:
Whose fruitlesse liues were vnder furrow sowne,
And sow vaine sorrow in a fruitlesse eare,
What is there else, but cease these fruitlesse paines,
Lo recreant (sayd he) the fruitlesse end
Like fruitlesse braunches, which the hatchets slight
Sad be the sights, and bitter fruits of warre,
With hearbs and fruits, whose kinds mote not be red:
Most famous fruits of matrimoniall bowre,
Which seeme to labour vnder their fruits lode:
To weet great store of forrest frute, which hee
That so rich frute should be from vs bereft;
That of his loue he reapt the timely frute,
They fall to strokes, the frute of too much talke:
And mother of a frutefull heritage,
Yet seem'd the soyle both fayre and frutefull eft,
And the frutes of the forrest was their feast:
Whereas the damned ghosts in torments fry,
And them before, the fry of children young
Nor fry in hartlesse griefe and dolefull teene.
Ye might haue seene the frothy billowes fry
Witnesse th'exceeding fry, which there are fed,
Her inward brest, and in her entrayles fryde,
Frï¿½lissa was as faire, as faire mote bee,
A Fter long stormes and tempests ouerblowne,
To seeke the fugitiue, both farre and nere,
He also gaue to fugitiues of Spayne,
Who long before awoke (for she ful ill
The charme fulfild, dead suddenly he downe did sincke.
After she had nine moneths fulfild and gone:
Onely what needeth, shall be here fulfild,
Each stroue to please, and others pleasure to fulfill.
And did like an halfe Theatre fulfill:
And do by all dew meanes thy destiny fulfill.
That I the same should faithfully fulfill,
Graunt him your grace, but so that he fulfill
Had neede haue mightie hands, for to fulfill
Which she could doe to Knights, which now she doth fulfill.
I haue forbore this duetie to fulfill:
But that I needes must by all meanes fulfill
Her reliques Fulgent hauing gathered,
Full iolly knight he seemd, and faire did sitt,
Vnder a vele, that wimpled was full low,
But full of fire and greedy hardiment,
Most lothsom, filthie, foule, and full of vile disdaine.
Full of great lumpes of flesh and gobbets raw,
Her vomit full of bookes and papers was,
That from her body full of filthie sin
Groning full deadly, all with troublous feare,
Amid the bowels of the earth full steepe,
Full of the makers guile, with vsage sly
Full enuious that night so long his roome did fill.
Where that false couple were full closely ment
Full iolly knight he seemde, and well addrest,
Sans foy: full large of limbe and euery ioint
Where Boreas doth blow full bitter bleake,
Where now enclosd in wooden wals full faste,
Full of sad feare and ghastly dreriment,
Hunting full greedie after saluage blood;
Full fast she fled, ne euer lookt behynd,
Who full of ghastly fright and cold affray,
Full strongly armd, and on a courser free,
And full of wrath, that with his sharp-head speare
But her fierce seruant full of kingly awe
With gaping iawes full greedy at him came,
Full of faire windowes, and delightfull bowres;
But full great pittie, that so faire a mould
And fall away, it mounted was full hie,
And full of Argus eyes their tailes dispredden wide.
Full of diseases was his carcas blew,
In a greene gowne he clothed was full faire,
Full of vaine follies, and new fanglenesse:
With precious mettall full, as they might hold,
A grieuous gout tormented him full sore,
He clothed was, ypainted full of eyes;
Full many mischiefes follow cruell VVrath;
No knight, but treachour full of false despight
And for his sake haue felt full many an heauie stowre.
The knight was fiers, and full of youthly heat:
And all the while Duessa wept full bitterly.
Doth weepe full sore, and sheddeth tender teares:
Which through the tre[m]bling leaues full gently playes
And all his sences stound, that still he lay full low.
And triple crowne set on her head full hye,
Thereby his mortall blade full comely hong
And scaly tayle was stretcht adowne his backe full low.
With sprincled pearle, and gold full richly drest,
Full many knights aduenturous and stout
Did grone full grieuous vnderneath the blow,
The proud Duessa full of wrathfull spight,
Came hurtling in full fierce, and forst the knight retyre.
That to the ground it doubleth him full low
Who answerd him full soft, he could not tell.
There all within full rich arayd he found,
Full hard it is (quoth he) to read aright
Her daintie limbes full softly down did lay:
O fairest virgin, full of heauenly light,
Musing full sadly in his sullein mind;
With lookes full lowly cast, and gate full slow,
With lookes full lowly cast, and gate full slow,
And toward them full matronely did pace.
Full of great loue, but Cupids wanton snare
His mind was full of spirituall repast,
Or like that sacred hill, whose head full hie,
Their heauenly notes, and make full many a louely lay.
He rousd himselfe full blith, and hastned them vntill.
His aery plumes doth rouze, full rudely dight,
Is gathered full, and worketh speedy way:
The percing steele there wrought a wound full wyde,
Then full of griefe and anguish vehement,
Full of great vertues, and for med'cine good.
With folded hands and knees full lowly bent
To him assembled with one full consort,
But they him layd full low in dungeon deepe,
In full content he there did long enioy,
And forth he fares full of malicious mind,
His carriage was full comely and vpright,
Full loth she seemd thereto, but yet did faine;
Then casting vp a deadly looke, full low,
With lips full pale and foltring tongue opprest,
Full measured three quarters of her yeare,
Full litle weenest thou, what sorrowes are
To proofe of passing wonders hath full often vsd.
Full of disport, still laughing, loosely light,
Purloynd both steed and speare, and ran away full light.
Her iuorie forhead, full of bountie braue,
With curious antickes, and full faire aumayld:
And eke her face ill fauourd, full of wrinckles old.
Full fast away, and did her quite forsake;
Stared full wide, and threw forth sparkes of fire,
Full oft approu'd in many a cruell warre,
One in bright armes embatteiled full strong,
And when him running in full course he spies,
That streight on ground made him full low to lye;
Full many doughtie knights he in his dayes
Was shot vp high, full of the stately tree,
Therewith she sweetly smyld. They though full bent,
And downe them poured through an hole full wide,
Sterne was his looke, and full of stomacke vaine,
And euery pillour decked was full deare
In which full many soules do endlesse waile and weepe.
That drenched lay full deepe, vnder the Garden side.
For now three dayes of men were full outwrought,
But full of anger fiercely to him cride;
But full of Princely bounty and great mind,
Full liuely is the semblaunt, though the substance dead.
Yet full of grace and goodly modestee,
A carefull man, and full of comely guise:
That him full of melancholy did shew;
Of those that roome was full, and them among
That were all worme-eaten, and full of canker holes.
And in their entrails, full of quicke Brimston,
Without full point, or other Cesure right,
Full large he was of limbe, and shoulders brode,
Which with a staffe, all full of litle snags
And his mischieuous bow full readie bent,
Full litle wanted, but he had him slaine,
That once hath failed of her souse full neare,
That made his spright to grone full piteous:
Aboue three furlongs, taking his full course,
To take him from his steed full tenderly,
Till that the Palmer gan full bitterly
In which full many had with haplesse doole
Who all attonce, gaping full greedily,
And his braue shield, full of old moniments,
Full many Countries they did ouerronne,
Full of disdainefull wrath, he fierce vprose,
Their puissance, whylome full dernely tryde:
Full griesly seem'd: therein they long did ryde,
Full of great enuie and fell gealosy,
For whose deare sake full many a bitter stownd,
And all was full of Damzels, and of Squires,
For she was full of amiable grace,
Full easie was for her to haue beliefe,
Into his hidden net full easily doth fall.
Did smyle full smoothly at her weetlesse wofull stound.
Sad, solemne, sowre, and full of fancies fraile
But sleepe full farre away from her did fly:
Full many wayes within her troubled mind,
Full many waies she sought, but none could find,
Thou her afford, full shortly I her dead shall see.
But his sonne Malgo shall full mightily
When the full time prefixt by destiny,
The Damzell was full deepe empassioned,
For ere two hundred yeares be full outronne,
Tho when the terme is full accomplishid,
Which haue full many feats aduenturous
A goodly Armour, and full rich aray,
Tho to their ready Steeds they clombe full light,
Strooke her full on the brest, that made her downe
And full of subtile sophismes, which do play
Tho full of bitter griefe and pensiue thought,
And full of fiery zeale, him followed long,
Full myld to her he spake, and oft let fall
So may ye gaine to you full great renowme,
Who all this while full hardly was assayd
Till he had made amends, and full restore
Full of fiers fury, and indignant hate,
Full of soft passion and vnwonted smart:
The goodly Mayd full of diuinities,
Which still increast, till she her terme had full outgone.
In which full many louely Nymphes abyde,
So may he long himselfe full easie hide:
So saying euery Nymph full narrowly she eyde.
To which the Damzell full of doubtfull thought,
At that same last extremitie full sore,
Full of sad feare, and doubtfull agony,
Full many wounds in his corrupted flesh
(Thereat full hartely laughed Satyrane.)
Full little weened I, that chastitee
Her sharpe rebuke full litle did esteeme;
And with his frory lips full softly kist,
Yet has full large to liue, and spend at libertie.
He came, which full of guests he found whyleare,
Both were full loth to leaue that needfull tent,
And both full loth in darkenesse to debate;
Yet both full liefe him lodging to haue lent,
And both full liefe his boasting to abate;
Full many yeares, and weetlesse wandered
Were ouerthrowne and layd on th'earth full cold,
Full deepe emplonged was, and drowned nye,
The iolly Satyres full of fresh delight,
And of their louely fellowship full glade,
Vpon his hands and feete he crept full light,
And to his wife, that now full soundly slept,
Depeincted was, full easie to be knowne,
Did beat and bounse his head and brest full sore;
There was he painted full of burning darts,
All which together sung full chearefully
In full straunge notes was sweetly heard to sound,
But Fury was full ill appareiled
He looking lompish and full sullein sad,
She chearefull fresh and full of ioyance glad,
Full of sad signes, fearefull to liuing sight;
Of which full proud, himselfe vp rearing hye,
Full dreadfully he shooke that all did quake,
There were full many moe like maladies,
Full dreadfull things out of that balefull booke
And euery part to safety full sound,
With her owne trusty Squire, both full of feare,
Of loue full manie lessons did apply,
Full many piteous stories doe remaine,
That I with teares full oft doe pittie it,
Full many things so doubtfull to be wayd,
And sayd, her loue to lose she was full loth,
That seem'd full hard t'accord two things so far in dout.
Her false Duessa who full well did know,
The barren ground was full of wicked weedes,
And made full goodly ioyance to her new found mate.
His fickle mind full of inconstancie.
That whether were more false, full hard it is to tell.
He was full wo, and gan his former griefe renew.
Which when he thought, it grieued him full sore,
He woxe full blithe, as he had got thereby,
Fond Squire, full angry then sayd Paridell,
All full of wrath, thus fiercely him bespake;
Full many knights, that loued her like deare,
Full many Lords, and many Knights her loued,
And courage full of haughtie hardiment,
Their mother was, and had full blessed hap,
Departed thence with full contended mynd;
Full many mightie strokes on either side
Full many strokes, that mortally were ment,
Full lightly, ere himselfe he could recower,
Sir Triamond at last full faint and feeble stood.
Is often seene full freshly to haue florisht,
Whereof full blith, eftsoones his mightie hand
In th'arm-pit full, that through both sides the wound appeard.
Whereof full glad for thirst, ech drunk an harty draught.
But Blandamour full of vainglorious spright,
At which they all gan laugh full merrily:
On th'other side, full many a warlike swaine,
Leading his friend away, full sorie to his vew.
Full many deedes that day were shewed plaine:
In quyent disguise, full hard to be descride.
Whereat full inly wroth was Triamond,
Full many others at him likewise ran:
